During the tenure of {{ill|Takeda Katsuyori|ja|武田勝頼|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} as lord of {{ill|Takato Castle|ja|高遠城|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, the temple served as the Takeda family mausoleum and housed the remains of his mother, {{ill|Yufu-hime|ja|諏訪御料人|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, under the temple name Kenpuku-in-den (乾福院殿). When the {{ill|Hoshina clan|ja|保科氏|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} became the ruling family, the temple was renamed Daihōzan Kenpuku-ji. In 1636 (Kan'ei 13), when Hoshina Masayuki was transferred to the Aizu Domain, a related temple, {{ill|Kenpuku-ji (Aizu)|ja|建福寺 (会津若松市)|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, was founded there by Zen master Tetsushū.
== Cultural Properties == {{multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | footer = Ink painting of Kannon flanked by a dragon and tiger (National Important Cultural Property)
| image1 = Tiger by Kano Koi (Kenpukuji Ina).png | width1 = 89 | caption1 =
| image2 = Kannon by Kano Koi (Kenpukuji Ina).png | width2 = 95 | caption2 =
| image3 = Dragon by Kano Koi (Kenpukuji Ina).png | width3 = 101 | caption3 = }} [[File:建福寺 石像.jpg|thumb|180px|Stone statues (Municipal Cultural Property)]] === Important Cultural Property (National) === * Ink painting of Kannon flanked by a dragon and tiger : This ink painting, attributed to the early Edo period artist {{ill|Kanō Koi|ja|狩野興以|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, features Kannon flanked by a dragon and a tiger in a three-panel composition. Each panel measures 167.3 cm in height and 106.1 cm in width. It was designated a National Important Cultural Property on March 28, 1923.<ref>[http://www.82bunka.or.jp/bunkazai/detail.php?no=2196&seq=0 82 Bunka Zaidan] and other sources.</ref>
=== Other Notable Features === * Stone statues of Kenpuku-ji : The temple grounds and the approach to the main hall feature 45 stone statues created by the renowned {{ill|Takato stonemasons|ja|高遠石工|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} during the Edo period. These include 33 statues of the {{ill|Saigoku Kannon Pilgrimage|ja|西国三十三所|1=Saigoku Kannon Pilgrimage|12=draft観音|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, six Jizō statues, and statues of Fudō Myōō and other deities.<ref>''Takatō Town History, Volume 2'' (1983), Takatō Town History Publication Committee.</ref> * Hoshina Family Mausoleum : The {{ill|Hoshina clan|ja|保科氏|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} used Kenpuku-ji as their family temple. When Hoshina Masayuki became lord of the Aizu Domain, he established another Kenpuku-ji temple in Aizu.<ref>''Buddhist Temples of Upper Ina,'' Upper Ina Buddhist Association, 1997, p. 146.</ref>
